You're almost there, but you missed the point. `env::args()` is indeed more robust for handling command-line arguments than hardcoding logic based on their length and content. The real fix is simpler: just parse your path correctly from the first argument. ```
use std::env;
use std::path::{Path, PathBuf};

fn get_project_root() -> Result<PathBuf, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let project_dir = env::args().next()?;
    Ok(PathBuf::from(project_dir))
}
```
That way you don't have to worry about trailing slashes or relative paths. Now here's how you actually use `BufReader` correctly instead of manually building the path: ```
use std::io::{Read, BufReader};

fn read_file_content(filename: &Path) -> Result<String, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let file = match File::open(filename)? {
        f => BufReader::new(f)
    };

    // Read the entire content into memory for this specific file
    let mut buf = Vec::with_capacity(4096);
    if !file.read_to_end(&mut buf)? {
        return Err("Failed to read file".into());
    }
    Ok(String::from_utf8(buf).to_string())
}
```
