That's actually pretty common when you're just starting out! It means your file handle isn't fully buffered yet. Here's a quick example to see how it looks with `BufReader`: 

```rust
use std::fs::{File, BufReader};
use std::io::Read;

fn read_file_content(file: &File) -> Result<String, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let mut reader = BufReader::new(file);
    let mut content = String::new();

    match reader.read_to_string(&mut content) {
        Ok(_) => return Ok(content),
        Err(e) if e.kind() == std::io::ErrorKind::UnexpectedEof => {}
        _ => return Err(Box::new(e)),
    }

    Ok(content)
}

fn main() {
    let file_path = "example.txt";
    let file = File::open(file_path).unwrap();

    // This is where the magic happens - it's not blocking! 
    match read_file_content(&file) {
        Ok(content) => println!("Got content: {}", content),
        Err(e) => eprintln!("Error reading file: {:?}", e),
    }
}
```

The key takeaway is that `BufReader` lets you peek at the end of the stream without actually reading everything into memory yet, which makes it super efficient for large files.

