So `PathBuf` is basically your custom string that lives on the filesystem, and you can do all those cool things without worrying about backslashes or forward slashes!

Definitely! I've been thinking about how efficient `BufReader` is when dealing with binary streams. Let's say you're parsing a JSON file or a protobuf message - those are usually all text-based, but if they end up in a binary format, the buffering logic still applies. Here's a quick example of what that looks like:

```rust
use std::fs::{File, BufReader};

fn parse_binary_file(path: &str) -> Result<Vec<u8>, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let file = File::open(path)?;

    // Create a buffered reader for binary data
    let mut buffer_reader = BufReader::new(file);

    match buffer_reader.read_to_end(&mut vec![0u8]) {
        Ok(_) => Ok(vec![0u8]),
        Err(e) if e.kind() == std::io::ErrorKind::UnexpectedEof => Ok(vec![]),
        _ => return Err(Box::new(e)),
    }
}

fn main() {
    let path = "binary_data.bin";
    match parse_binary_file(path) {
        Ok(data) => println!("Parsed {} bytes of binary data", data.len()),
        Err(e) => eprintln!("Error: {:?}", e),
    }
}
```

The key insight is that `BufReader` works on top of any stream, so you can read from it whether the underlying file is text or binary. It just needs to tell you when the end-of-stream marker appears.
